A life of indolence, however, could never have given either Epicurus, or Lucretius, that truly wonderful extent of knowledge, that deep re- search into the most curious phaenomena of nature, and that power of argumentatively elucidating their own doctrines from facts, and, for the most part, from facts alone, which are to be traced in almost every page of this inimitable poem. And as to their corporeal pleasures let the passage before us speak, a passage perfectly consonant with the general pre- cepts and practice of their system, and in which we meet with a rigid‚ and almost anchorite abjuration of every thing the world calls gratification or indul- gence. In reality‚ the pleasures pursued and re- commended :by Epicurus were entirely of the nega- tive kind: pleasures easily procured, and almost in every instance devoid of mutability.
